article.headline: McCarville leads Gophers with 15 points, 11 boards
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Minnesota's misery in the Big Ten tournament
is finally over.

Janel McCarville scored 15 points and grabbed 11 rebounds,
leading the 18th-ranked Golden Gophers to a 68-47 victory over
Northwestern for their first conference tournament win since 1997.

"History has shown that we haven't won a game since I don't
know when," coach Pam Borton said. "So it's our first win in the
Big Ten, so we're really excited."

Entering this year's first-round game, the postseason tournament
had been an abomination for the Gophers. Their 1-10 record was the
Big Ten's worst and their run of six straight tournament losses was
the longest active streak among the conference's 11 teams.

When the final buzzer sounded, Minnesota's career scoring
leader, Lindsay Whalen, pumped her fist in the air as the band
played the school's fight song.

And the sixth-seeded Gophers already were thinking about their
rematch with No. 22 Ohio State in Friday's quarterfinals. The
Buckeyes, seeded third, swept Minnesota this year.

"We've got to start off a lot stronger than we did tonight,"
Borton said. "We've got to take better shots, take care of the
ball and hit a few more 3s than we did tonight."

The Gophers (21-7) didn't even need Whalen, who missed her sixth
straight game with two broken bones in her right hand.

McCarville helped dominate the middle, where the Gophers
outrebounded the Wildcats 51-25. McCarville had help from Kadidja
Anderson, who had 14 points and 11 rebounds, and Jamie Broback, who
had nine points and 10 rebounds.

The Wildcats were simply overwhelmed. Samantha McComb led the
Northwestern with 16 points but it wasn't nearly enough to avoid a
16th loss in 17 games.

"We took some tough hits," Northwestern coach June Olkowski
said. "They took our cuts away, or tried to. We took a lot of open
shots, but we didn't convert."

Although Minnesota made this one look easy, it didn't come
without a scare.

Whalen and McCarville, the Gophers' second-leading scorer, were
both on the bench for the final 6:14 of the first half after
McCarville took a nasty spill while fighting for an offensive
rebound.

McCarville tried to go over the top of a Wildcats player, then
landed hard on her stomach and was sprawled on the floor for a few
moments before walking off.

That seemed to get the Gophers out of a sluggish rut, though.

On Minnesota's next possession, Broback put in a layup to break
a 15-15 tie. The Gophers then scored 14 of the half's final 16
points to take a 27-19 lead at the half.

"They went after our mismatch," Olkowski said. "Minnesota
pounded the ball in to Broback."

When McCarville returned to start the second half, Minnesota
wasted little time in taking control. Another 12-4 run made it
39-23 with 15:16 left and the Wildcats never got closer than 12 the
rest of the way.

For the Gophers, there was a sense of relief.

"We came in ready to get down to business," McCarville said.
"Over the past couple weeks it built up to this. This was a big
game for us."
